ek.jpeg|Chandran Rutnam with [[John Derek]] and [[Bo Derek]]\nFile:Harrison Ford and Chandran Rutnam in Sri Lanka.jpg|[[Harrison Ford]] and Chandran Rutnam on the set of ''[[Indiana Jones and the Temple of Doom]]'' which was shot in Hantana, Sri Lanka in 1983\nFile:Steven Spielberg with Chandran Rutnam in Sri Lanka.jpg|[[Steven Spielberg]] and Chandran Rutnam on location in Sri Lanka during the filming of ''[[Indiana Jones and the Temple of Doom]]''\nFile:Chandranratnum2.JPG|Rutnam with [[Steven Spielberg]] at a benefit honoring Spielberg (December 9, 2009)\nFile:Anton Wickremasinghe, Chandran Rutnam and Alfred Hitchcock at the Academy Awards in Los Angeles.jpeg|Anton Wickremasinghe, Chandran Rutnam (center) and [[Alfred Hitchcock]] at the [[Academy Awards]] in Los Angeles.\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Evelyn Rutnam Institute for Inter-Cultural Studies]]\n* [[Cinema of Sri Lanka]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Chandran Rutnam}}\n* {{IMDb name|0752110}}\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Gs99BJEs6Kc ''Uththareethara: Chandran Rutnam'' (documentary video)]\n\n{{authority control}}\n{{Sinhala Cinema|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rutnam, Chandran}}\n[[Category:Sri Lankan Tamil film directors]]\n[[Category:Sinhalese people]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English-language film directors]]\n[[Category:Film producers from California]]\n[[Category:American film directors of Sri Lankan descent]]\n[[Category:American male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Sri Lankan emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Sri Lankan Tamil film producers]]\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from California]]\n[[Category:American film editors]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toLionair(link changed toLionair (Sri Lanka); link changed toLionair (Sri Lanka); link changed toLionair (Sri Lanka); link changed toLionair (Sri Lanka)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chandran_Rutnam"}
{"title_page": "Arta, Greece", "text_new": "{{Infobox Greek Dimos\n |name = Arta\n |name_local = \u0386\u03c1\u03c4\u03b1\n |image_map = 2011 Dimos Artas.png\n |image_skyline = Arta Bridge 9.jpg\n |caption_skyline = View of the [[Bridge of Arta]] over the [[Arachthos (river)|Arachthos river]]\n |periph = [[Epirus (region)|Epirus]]\n |periphunit         =  [[Arta (regional unit)|Arta]]\n |pop_municipality   = 43166\n |area_municipality  = 457.2\n |pop_municunit      = 27330\n |area_municunit     = 47.973\n |pop_community      = 24427\n |population_as_of = 2011\n |demonym            = Artean<br>(Greek: Artinos)\n |elevation = 30\n |coordinates        = {{coord|39|09|54|N|20|59|15|E|display=inline,title}}\n |postal_code = 471 00\n |area_code = 26810\n |licence = \u0391\u03a4\n |mayor = Christos Tsirogiannis([[New Democracy]])\n |website = [http://www.arta.gr www.arta.gr]\n |city_flag          = \n |city_seal          = \n |districts          = \n |party              = \n |since              = \n |elevation_min      = \n |elevationArta is really cool ma dudes l unit)|regional unit of Arta]], which is part of [[Epirus (region)|Epirus]] region. The city was known in ancient times as [[Ambracia]] ({{lang-grc|\u1f08\u03bc\u03b2\u03c1\u03b1\u03ba\u03af\u03b1}}). Arta is known for the [[Bridge of Arta|medieval bridge]] over the [[Arachthos River]]. Arta is also known for its ancient sites from the era of [[Pyrrhus of Epirus]] and its well-preserved 13th-century castle. Arta's [[Byzantine]] history is reflected in its many [[Byzantine]] churches; perhaps the best known is the [[Panagia Paregoretissa]] (Mother of God the Consoling), built about 1290 by [[despot (court title)|Despot]] [[Nikephoros I Komnenos Doukas]]. The city is the seat of the [[Technological Educational Institute of Epirus]].\n\n==History==\n\n===Antiquity===\n{{main|Ambracia}}\nThe first settlement in the area of the modern city dates to the 9th century B.C. Ambracia was founded as a [[Corinth]]ian [[colonies in antiquity|colony]] in the 7th century B.C. In 294 BC, after forty-three years of semi-autonomy under [[Macedon]]ian suzerainty, Ambracia was given to [[Pyrrhus of Epirus|Pyrrhus]], king of the [[Molossians]] and of [[Epirus (ancient state)|Epirus]], who made it his capital, using Ambracia as a base to attack the [[Roman Republic|Romans]]. Pyrrhus managed to achieve great but costly victories against the Romans, hence the phrase \"[[Pyrrhic victory]]\" which refers in particular to an exchange at the [[Battle of Asculum]]. Nevertheless, Pyrrhus found the time and means to adorn his capital with a palace, temples and theatres. In 146 BC, Ambracia became part of the [[Roman Republic]].\n\n===Middle Ages===\n{{further|Byzantine Greece}}\n\nDespite the existence several churches from the 9th and 10th centuries, Arta is first attested only in 1082, when the [[Normans]] under [[Bohemond I of Antioch|Bohemond]] laid siege to the city.{{sfn|Soustal|Koder|1981|page=113}} The origin and etymology of the name is uncertain and debated.{{sfn|Soustal|Koder|1981|page=114}} In the [[Komnenian period]], the city flourished as a commercial centre, with links to [[Venice]], and rose to become a [[bishopric]] by&nbsp;1157.{{sfn|Soustal|Koder|1981|page=113}}<ref name=\"ODB\">{{ODB | last = Gregory | first = Timothy E. | last2 = \u0160ev\u010denko | first2 = Nancy Patterson | title = Arta | pages = 191\u2013192 }}</ref> The Jewish traveller [[Benjamin of Tudela]] visited the area in 1165.{{sfn|Soustal|Koder|1981|page=113}}\n\n[[File:Church of St. Theodora (Arta) 3.jpg|thumb|left|Byzantine church of St [[Theodora of Arta]] (11th century)]]\n[[File:Byzantium1204.png|thumb|The [[Despotate of Epirus]] (green) in 1204]]\n\nBy the end of the 12th century, Arta probably formed a distinct fiscal district (''[[episkepsis]]'') within the wider [[theme (Byzantine district)|theme]] of [[Nicopolis (theme)|Nicopolis]].<ref name=\"ODB\"/> After the [[Siege of Constantinople (1204)|fall]] of [[Constantinople]] to the [[Fourth Crusade]], it is recorded as the ''pertinentia de Arta'' in the ''[[Partitio Romaniae]]'' treaty of 1204, and assigned to Venice.{{sfn|Soustal|Koder|1981|page=113}}\n\n[[File:\u0397 \u03a0\u03b1\u03c1\u03b7\u03b3\u03bf\u03c1\u03ae\u03c4\u03b9\u03c3\u03c3\u03b1.jpg|thumb|right|The 13th-century [[Church of the Parigoritissa]], formerly site of the [[Archaeological Collection of Arta]].]]\n[[File:Byzantine church of st Vasileios in Arta, Greece.jpg|thumb|Saint Basilios of the Agor\u00e1 (14-15th century)]]\n\nThe Venetians did not take control, however, for in 1205 [[Michael I Komnenos Doukas]] came to the city, succeeded its previous Byzantine governor, and quickly established a new principality, which is known by historians as the [[Despotate of Epirus]].{{sfn|Soustal|Koder|1981|page=113}} Arta remained the capital of the new principality for most of its history,{{sfn|Soustal|Koder|1981|page=113}} and flourished as a result. The city experienced considerable building activity, with the renovation of older churches and the construction of new ones, most notably the [[Church of the Parigoritissa]] and the [[Church of the Kato Panagia]].<ref name=\"ODB\"/> Sometime after 1227 it received fortifications,<ref name=\"ODB\"/> and was the site of regional Church councils in 1213, 1219, and 1225.{{sfn|Soustal|Koder|1981|page=113}} The 15th-century ''[[Chronicle of the Tocco]]'' describes it as \"the center of a fertile agricultural region with many water buffaloes, cows, and horses\". The city had trade links to Venice\u2014a Venetian consul is attested in 1284 and 1314/19{{sfn|Soustal|Koder|1981|page=113}}\u2014and Ragusa, exporting dried meat, lard, ham, furs, and [[indigo]]. Archaeological finds also attest to a local ceramic industry.<ref name=\"ODB\"/>\n\nAfter the [[Battle of Pelagonia]] in 1259, the city was occupied by the troops of the rival [[Byzantine Greeks|Greek]] successor state, the [[Empire of Nicaea]], (which restored the Byzantine Empire in 1261) but was soon recovered for Epirus by [[John I Doukas]].{{sfn|Soustal|Koder|1981|page=113}} Another attack by the Byzantine emperor [[Andronikos II Palaiologos]] in 1292, by land and sea, was unsuccessful.{{sfn|Soustal|Koder|1981|page=113}} In 1303, the city was besieged for a month by the [[Capetian House of Anjou|Angevins]] under [[Charles II of Naples]].{{sfn|Soustal|Koder|1981|page=113}} In 1313, much of the city was destroyed in a great fire.{{sfn|Soustal|Koder|1981|page=113}} In the next year, Byzantine troops under the ''[[pinkernes]]'' John attacked Epirus, including Arta.{{sfn|Soustal|Koder|1981|page=113}}\n\nIn 1318, the last male-line descendant of Michael I, [[Thomas I Komnenos Doukas]], was assassinated by his nephew, the [[Count of Cephalonia]] [[Nicholas Orsini]], and Epirus passed to the Italian [[Orsini]] family. Nicholas was in turn murdered in 1323 by his brother [[John II Orsini]]. In 1331 Arta, as well as [[Leucas]] and other areas, were occupied by [[Walter VI of Brienne]], and John Orsini was forced to accept Angevin suzerainty.{{sfn|Soustal|Koder|1981|page=113}} John's death in 1335 left Epirus in the weak hands of the young [[Nikephoros II Orsini]] and his mother [[Anna Palaiologina (daughter of Andronikos Angelos Palaiologos)|Anna Palaiologina]], and the Byzantine emperor [[Andronikos III Palaiologos]] availed himself of the opportunity to occupy and annex Epirus.{{sfn|Fine|1994|pp=253\u2013254}}\n\nByzantine rule was unpopular,{{sfn|Nicol|2010|pp=108ff}} and in 1339 a revolt broke out, with Arta joining it, under a certain Nicholas Basilitzes. Andronikos III and his commander-in-chief, [[John Kantakouzenos]], campaigned in person in Epirus and captured the rebel fortresses one by one, either by siege or through negotiations. By the end of 1340, Byzantine rule was restored, and [[John Angelos (sebastokrator)|John Angelos]] took his seat as imperial governor in Arta.{{sfn|Fine|1994|pp=254\u2013255}}{{sfn|Nicol|2010|pp=114\u2013121, 124}}\n\n[[File:The Greek defensive barrack of Arta, 1881.jpg|thumb|The Greek defensive barrack, 1881]]\n[[File:Clock Tower Arta Greece 5.jpg|thumb|Old photo of Arta with the clocktower, 1910]]\n\nAided by the [[Byzantine civil war of 1341\u20131347]] and an outbreak of the [[Black Death]] that devastated the region, Arta with the rest of Epirus fell under the rule of the [[Medieval Serbia|Serbian]] king [[Stefan Dushan]] in autumn 1347. Dushan's half-brother [[Simeon Uro\u0161]], who married John II Orsini's daughter [[Thomais Orsini]], was appointed governor of Epirus.{{sfn|Fine|1994|p=320}} The city remained part of the new [[Serbian Empire]] until Dushan's death in 1355. Nikephoros II Orsini recovered Epirus in 1356/7, but his death in the [[Battle of Achelous (1359)|Battle of Achelous]] against the [[Albanians|Albanian]] tribes that had invaded the region, meant that Arta returned to the (rather nominal) rule of Simeon Uro\u0161, who preferred to reside in [[Thessaly]] rather than Epirus.{{sfn|Soustal|Koder|1981|pp=70, 113\u2013114}}{{sfn|Fine|1994|pp=347\u2013350}}{{sfn|Nicol|2010|pp=123\u2013138}} This left Epirus open to increasing Albanian migration, who soon captured most of Epirus, except for [[Ioannina]].{{sfn|Fine|1994|pp=350\u2013351}} In 1367 or shortly after, Arta too was captured, and became the centre of the \"[[Despotate of Arta]]\", until 1374 under [[Peter Losha]] and then [[John Bua Spata]].{{sfn|Soustal|Koder|1981|page=114}} The Albanian rulers managed to withstand attacks by the Angevins (sometime between 1374 and 1384), as well as by the [[Grand Master of the Knights Hospitaller]] [[Juan Fern\u00e1ndez de Heredia]] in 1378, but in 1384 the city was plundered by the [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman Turks]].{{sfn|Soustal|Koder|1981|page=114}}\n\nFrom 1401/02, [[Carlo I Tocco]], the ambitious Count of Cephalonia, began launching attacks on Arta, taking advantage of the Albanians' infighting. Despite the Albanians' calling on Ottoman aid, in 1416 Tocco captured Arta after a long siege. Having taken control of Ioannina in 1411, Tocco thus reunited the core of the old Epirote realm, and received recognition from both the Ottomans and the Byzantine emperor.{{sfn|Soustal|Koder|1981|pp=72\u201373, 114}} After Carlo I's death in 1429, he was succeeded by his nephew [[Carlo II Tocco]]. In 1449, the city fell to the Ottomans.{{sfn|Soustal|Koder|1981|page=114}}\n\n===Ottoman period===\n{{further|Ottoman Greece}}\n\nUnder Ottoman rule, the town was called in Turkish ''Narda''. It was occupied by [[Republic of Venice|Venetians]] in 1717 and the French in 1797, but the Ottomans retook it in 1799. Several battles took place near the city during the [[Greek War of Independence]].\n\n===Modern era===\nThe city was finally annexed to the [[Greek Kingdom]] in 1881 with the [[Convention of Constantinople (1881)|Convention of Constantinople]].\n\n==Climate==\n\n{{Weather box\n|width=auto\n|location=Arta (1976-1997)\n|metric first=yes\n|single line=yes\n|Jan high C=13.3\n|Feb high C=14.0\n|Mar high C=16.7\n|Apr high C=20.1\n|May high C=25.0\n|Jun high C=29.1\n|Jul high C=31.8\n|Aug high C=32.0\n|Sep high C=29.0\n|Oct high C=24.1\n|Nov high C=19.0\n|Dec high C=14.9\n|year high C=\n|Jan mean C=8.7\n|Feb mean C=9.4\n|Mar mean C=11.9\n|Apr mean C=15.2\n|May mean C=19.9\n|Jun mean C=24.0\n|Jul mean C=26.5\n|Aug mean C=26.5\n|Sep mean C=23.1\n|Oct mean C=18.3\n|Nov mean C=13.5\n|Dec mean C=9.9\n|year mean C=\n|Jan low C=4.7\n|Feb low C=5.2\n|Mar low C=7.0\n|Apr low C=9.9\n|May low C=13.9\n|Jun low C=17.3\n|Jul low C=19.5\n|Aug low C=19.9\n|Sep low C=17.1\n|Oct low C=13.4\n|Nov low C=9.4\n|Dec low C=6.0\n|year low C=\n|rain colour = green\n|Jan rain mm=131.8\n|Feb rain mm=135.0\n|Mar rain mm=93.8\n|Apr rain mm=81.5\n|May rain mm=58.5\n|Jun rain mm=21.8\n|Jul rain mm=12.6\n|Aug rain mm=17.2\n|Sep rain mm=43.5\n|Oct rain mm=115.4\n|Nov rain mm=186.0\n|Dec rain mm=187.5\n|year rain mm=\n|Jan rain days=12.1\n|Feb rain days=11.1\n|Mar rain days=10.6\n|Apr rain days=9.6\n|May rain days=7.4\n|Jun rain days=4.2\n|Jul rain days=2.5\n|Aug rain days=2.5\n|Sep rain days=4.9\n|Oct rain days=8.1\n|Nov rain days=11.9\n|Dec rain days=13.0\n|year rain days=\n|Jan humidity=71.7\n|Feb humidity=70.6\n|Mar humidity=68.9\n|Apr humidity=68.8\n|May humidity=66.0\n|Jun humidity=61.4\n|Jul humidity=59.2\n|Aug humidity=59.4\n|Sep humidity=63.6\n|Oct humidity=67.7\n|Nov humidity=74.1\n|Dec humidity=73.2\n|year humidity=\n|source 1 = Hellenic National Meteorological Service <ref>{{cite web\n  | url=http://www.hnms.gr/hnms/greek/climatology/climatology_region_diagrams_html?dr_city=Arta\n  | title=Mean Arta Climatic Averages\n  | publisher=Hellenic National Meteorological Service\n  | accessdate=30 April 2015\n  | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160916091714/http://www.hnms.gr/hnms/greek/climatology/climatology_region_diagrams_html?dr_city=Arta\n  | archive-date=16 September 2016\n  | url-status=dead\n  }}</ref>\n  | date=April 2015\n}}\n\n==Landmarks==\n[[File:\u039d\u03b1\u03cc\u03c2 \u0391\u03c0\u03cc\u03bb\u03bb\u03c9\u03bd\u03b1 \u03a0\u03c5\u03b8\u03af\u03bf\u03c5 \u03a3\u03c9\u03c4\u03ae\u03c1\u03b1, \u0386\u03c1\u03c4\u03b1 1.JPG|thumb|Ruins of the ancient temple of Apollo P\u00fdthios Sot\u00edr]]\n[[File:Small theatre of Ambracia 1.jpg|thumb|Small ancient theatre]]\n\n===Classical===\nThe modern city is on the site of ancient [[Ambracia]]. Remains of the classic era include the ancient walls, the ruins of an ancient temple of [[Apollo]], a small theatre, and remnants of the southwest cemetery.\n\n===Byzantine and later===\n[[File:Arta Castle Greece 16.jpg|thumb|200px|View of the Byzantine castle]]\n[[File:Arta-clock tower.JPG|thumb|200px|Clocktower in front of the castle]]\n[[File:Kilkis square, Arta, Greece.jpg|thumb|200px|Kilkis Square]]\n[[File:Saint Demetrius church in Arta, Greece.jpg|thumb|200px|Saint Demetrius of Thessaloniki church]]\n[[File:Lake Arta Greece 5.JPG|thumb|200px|Artificial lake of Arta]]\n\nThe town's fortifications were built by [[Michael I Komnenos Doukas]] in the early 13th century, but their present form is largely post-Byzantine. Secular architecture from the Byzantine period, including the palace of the Despots of Epirus, has vanished completely, but the city preserves numerous churches.<ref name=\"ODB\"/>\n\nThe most important Byzantine church is the [[cathedral]] [[Church of the Paregoretissa]], built ca. 1290 by [[Nikephoros I Komnenos Doukas]] and his wife [[Anna Palaiologina Kantakouzene]]. Other important churches of the late Byzantine period are the [[Church of the Kato Panagia]], built by Nikephoros I's father [[Michael II Komnenos Doukas]], and the Monastery of Saint Theodora, housing the tomb of the city's patron, [[Theodora of Arta]].<ref name=\"ODB\"/> Several other churches dating to the 9th and 10th centuries also survive in and around the city: [[Saint Basil of the Bridge]], [[Saint Demetrios of Katsoures]] in [[Plisioi]], the [[Panagia Blacherna monastery]], the [[Panagia Vryoni]] in [[Neochoraki, Arta|Neochoraki]], the Red Church in [[Vourgareli]], the Panagia of Koronisia in [[Koronisia]] and the Church of the Pantanassa in [[Filippiada]].\n\n===Museums===\n*[[Archaeological Museum of Arta]]\n*[[Church of the Paregoretissa]]\n*Folk museum 'Skoufas'\n*Historical museum 'Skoufas'\n*Private folk museum in Kypseli.\n*Archaeological museum of Koronisia\n\n==Technological Educational Institute of Epirus==\n[[File:\u03a4\u03bc\u03ae\u03bc\u03b1 \u0391\u03bd\u03b8\u03bf\u03ba\u03bf\u03bc\u03af\u03b1\u03c2 \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u0391\u03c1\u03c7\u03b9\u03c4\u03b5\u03ba\u03c4\u03bf\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae\u03c2 \u03a4\u03bf\u03c0\u03af\u03bf\u03c5-\u03a4\u0395\u0399 \u0397\u03c0\u03b5\u03af\u03c1\u03bf\u03c5-\u0386\u03c1\u03c4\u03b1.JPG|thumb|A building of the [[Technological Educational Institute of Epirus]]]]\n\nThe Technological Educational Institute of Epirus (T.E.I.) [http://www.teiep.gr] has a main campus and its administration seat in Arta and has branch campuses in the three other main cities of Epirus, [[Ioannina]], [[Igoumenitsa]] and [[Preveza]]. It has four (4) Faculties and thirteen (13) Departments.\n\n==Transportation==\nArta is located NNW of [[Antirrio]], [[Messolongi]] and [[Agrinio]], NE of [[Preveza]], SSE of [[Ioannina]] and nearly SW of [[Trikala]].\n\nRegular bus lines connect Arta with all bigger Greek cities.\n(bus to Athens departs several times a day and trip takes about 5 hours)\n\nThe city is linked with the [[Greek National Road 5|GR-5]] (Antirrio - Ioannina) and the [[Greek National Road 30|GR-30]] which links with [[Peta, Greece|Peta]] and [[Trikala]].\nThe [[Arachthos River]] flows to the west with its reservoir lying directly to the north.\n\n==Municipality==\n[[File:2011 Dimos Artas.png|thumb|Arta municipality]]\n[[File:Nikolaos Skoufas pedestrian street in Arta, Greece.jpg|thumb|Skoufa Street]]\n[[File:Street market in Arta, Greece.jpg|thumb|Central street market]]\n\nThe present municipality Arta was formed at the 2011 local government reform by the merger of the following 5 former municipalities, that became municipal units (constituent communities in brackets):<ref name=Kallikratis>[http://www.kedke.gr/uploads2010/FEKB129211082010_kallikratis.pdf Kallikratis law] Greece Ministry of Interior {{in lang|el}}</ref>\n*[[Amvrakikos]] (Aneza, Vigla, Gavria, Kalogeriko, Koronisia, Polydroso, Rachi, Strongyli, Psathotopi)\n*'''Arta''' (Arta, Keramates, Kostakioi, [[Limini]])\n*[[Filothei, Arta|Filothei]] (Agios Spyridon, Kalamia, Kalovatos, Kirkizates, Rokka, Chalkiades)\n*[[Vlacherna]] (Vlacherna, Grammenitsa, Grimpovo, Korfovouni)\n*[[Xirovouni]] (Ammotopos, Dafnoti, Kampi, Pantanassa, Pistiana, Rodavgi, Skoupa, Faneromeni)\n\nThe municipality has an area of 457.248&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>, the municipal unit 47.493&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>.<ref name=stat01>{{cite web|url=http://dlib.statistics.gr/Book/GRESYE_02_0101_00098%20.pdf |publisher=National Statistical Service of Greece |title=Population & housing census 2001 (incl. area and average elevation) |language=el |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150921212047/http://dlib.statistics.gr/Book/GRESYE_02_0101_00098%20.pdf |archivedate=2015-09-21 }}</ref>\n\n===Quarters of Arta===\n*Agia Triada\n*Agioi Anargyroi\n*Agios Georgios Glykorrizou\n*Eleousa\n*Glykorrizo\n*Kato Panagia Artas\n*Marathovouni\n\n==Historical population==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- \n! Year !! Municipal unit !! Municipality\n|-\n| 1981 || 20,004 || -  \n|-\n| 1991 || 23,710 || - \n|-\n| 2001 || 23,863 || - \n|-\n| 2011 || 27,330 || 43,166 \n|}\n\n==Notable people==\n\n=== Ancient ===\n\n*[[Pyrrhus of Epirus|Pyrrhus]] (318 BC-272 BC), general and king of Epirus\n*[[Epicrates of Ambracia]] (4th century BC), comic poet\n*[[Silanus of Ambracia]] (5th century BC), soothsayer in [[Xenophon]]'s [[Anabasis (Xenophon)|''Anabasis'']]\n*[[Epigonus of Ambracia]] (6th-5th BC), musician\n\n=== Byzantine ===\n\n*[[Michael I Komnenos Doukas]], founder and first ruler of the [[Despotate of Epirus|principality of Epirus]] from 1205 until his death in 1215.\n*[[Theodore Komnenos Doukas]], (died c. 1253), ruler of [[Despotate of Epirus|Epirus]] from 1215 to 1230 and of Thessalonica from 1224 to 1230.\n* [[Theodora Petraliphaina]], [[canonized]] as '''Saint Theodora of Arta'''; (ca. 1225 \u2013 after 1270),  [[:wikt:consort|consort]] of [[Despotate of Epirus|Epirus]] and [[Eastern Orthodox Church|Orthodox Christian]] saint.\n* [[Michael II Komnenos Doukas]], ruler of [[Despotate of Epirus|Epirus]] from 1230 until his death in 1266/68.\n*[[Nikephoros I Komnenos Doukas]], (c. 1240 &ndash; c. 1297) ruler of [[Despotate of Epirus|Epirus]] from 1267/8 to c. 1297.\n* [[Thomas I Komnenos Doukas]],(c. 1285&ndash;1318) ruler of [[Despotate of Epirus|Epirus]] from c. 1297 until his death in 1318.\n\n=== Modern ===\n[[File:Skoufas.jpg|thumb|140px|[[Nikolaos Skoufas]]]]\n*[[Maximus the Greek]] (1475\u20131556),  monk, publicist, writer, scholar, humanist and translator\n*[[Nikolaos Skoufas]] (1779\u20131818), founder of the [[Filiki Eteria]], from [[Kompoti]]\n*[[Georgios Karaiskakis]] (1780\u20131827),hero of the [[Greek War of Independence]]\n*[[Theodoros Tzinis]] (1798\u20131869), fighter of the [[Greek War of Independence]], from [[Kompoti]]\n*[[Azmi \u00d6mer Akal\u0131n]], [[W\u0101li]] of [[Bursa]].<ref name=\"\u00d6zdalga2005\">{{cite book|last=\u00d6zdalga|first=Elisabeth|title=Late Ottoman society: the intellectual legacy|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sRtTyyGIgXsC&pg=PA332|accessdate=19 November 2010|year=2005|publisher=Psychology Press|isbn=978-0-415-34164-6|page=332}}</ref>\n*[[Hoca Ishak Efendi]] (1774\u20131835), Ottoman engineer and translator\n*[[Napoleon Zervas]] (1891\u20131957), WWII general and resistance leader\n*[[Konstantinos Karapanos]] (1840\u20131911),political and archaeologist\n*[[Alexandros Karapanos]] (1873\u20131946), politician and diplomat\n*[[Yiannis Moralis]] (1916-2009), painter\n*[[Olga Gerovasili]], politician\n*[[Antonios Nikopolidis]] (1971), footballer\n\n==Professional sports==\n'''Handball'''\n*https://web.archive.org/web/20070514042114/http://www.anagenisi-artas.gr/\n\n'''Basketball'''\n*[[Pyrros Artas]]\n\n'''Football'''\n*https://web.archive.org/web/20190207113340/http://www.anagenisiartas.gr/\n*https://web.archive.org/web/20061205033543/http://doxa-artas.gr/\n\n'''Volleyball'''\n*https://web.archive.org/web/20070516144231/http://www.anagenisi-artas.gr/volley/\n*http://www.filia.gr/\n\n==See also==\n*[[Despotate of Arta]]\n*[[Bridge of Arta]]\n*[[Arachthos River]]\n*[[Despotate of Epirus]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n{{refbegin|2}}\n* {{Cite book|ref=harv|last=Fine|first=John Van Antwerp Jr.|authorlink=John Van Antwerp Fine Jr.|title=The Late Medieval Balkans: A Critical Survey from the Late Twelfth Century to the Ottoman Conquest|year=1994|origyear=1987|location=Ann Arbor, Michigan|publisher=University of Michigan Press|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LvVbRrH1QBgC}}\n* {{cite book|last=Nicol|first=Donald MacGillivray|authorlink=Donald Nicol|title=The Despotate of Epiros 1267\u20131479: A Contribution to the History of Greece in the Middle Ages|location=Cambridge|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=2010|isbn=978-0-521-13089-9|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XIj0FfKto9AC|ref=harv}}\n* {{Tabula Imperii Byzantini | volume = 3}}\n* {{Cite book|ref=harv|last=Ze\u010devi\u0107|first=Nada|title=The Tocco of the Greek Realm: Nobility, Power and Migration in Latin Greece (14th-15th centuries)|year=2014|location=Belgrade|publisher=Makart|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LcqfAQAACAAJ}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.nomarxia-artas.gr Arta Prefecture]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060115070859/http://www.gtp.gr/LocPage.asp?id=2082 Municipality of Arta on GTP Travel Pages] (in English and Greek)\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060213105525/http://www.gtp.gr/LocPage.asp?id=2083 Arta (community) on GTP Travel Pages] (in English and Greek)\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110101160239/http://www.artasmuseum.gr/ Archaeological Museum of Arta] {{in lang|el}}\n\n{{Kallikratis-Epirus}}\n{{Arta div}}\n\n[[Category:Arta, Greece| ]]\n[[Category:Greek prefectural capitals]]\n[[Category:Municipalities of Epirus (region)]]\n[[Category:Burial sites of the Komnenodoukas dynasty]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Arta (regional unit)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Greek Dimos\n |name = Arta\n |name_local = \u0386\u03c1\u03c4\u03b1\n |image_map = 2011 Dimos Artas.png\n |image_skyline = Arta Bridge 9.jpg\n |caption_skyline = View of the [[Bridge of Arta]] over the [[Arachthos (river)|Arachthos river]]\n |periph = [[Epirus (region)|Epirus]]\n |periphunit         =  [[Arta (regional unit)|Arta]]\n |pop_municipality   = 43166\n |area_municipality  = 457.2\n |pop_municunit      = 27330\n |area_municunit     = 47.973\n |pop_community      = 24427\n |population_as_of = 2011\n |demonym            = Artean<br>(Greek: Artinos)\n |elevation = 30\n |coordinates        = {{coord|39|09|54|N|20|59|15|E|display=inline,title}}\n |postal_code = 471 00\n |area_code = 26810\n |licence = \u0391\u03a4\n |mayor = Christos Tsirogiannis([[New Democracy]])\n |website = [http://www.arta.gr www.arta.gr]\n |city_flag          = \n |city_seal          = \n |districts          = \n |party              = \n |since              = \n |elevation_min      = \n |elevation_max      = \n}}\n\n'''Arta''' ({{lang-el|\u0386\u03c1\u03c4\u03b1}}) is a city in northwestern [[Greece]], capital of the [[Arta (regional unit)|regional unit of Arta]], which is part of [[Epirus (region)|Epirus]] region. The city was known in ancient times as [[Ambracia]] ({{lang-grc|\u1f08\u03bc\u03b2\u03c1\u03b1\u03ba\u03af\u03b1}}). Arta is known for the [[Bridge of Arta|medieval bridge]] over the [[Arachthos River]]. Arta is also known for its ancient sites from the era of [[Pyrrhus of Epirus]] and its well-preserved 13th-century castle. Arta's [[Byzantine]] history is reflected in its many [[Byzantine]] churches; perhaps the best known is the [[Panagia Paregoretissa]] (Mother of God the Consoling), built about 1290 by [[despot (court title)|Despot]] [[Nikephoros I Komnenos Doukas]]. The city is the seat of the [[Technological Educational Institute of Epirus]].\n\n==History==\n\n===Antiquity===\n{{main|Ambracia}}\nThe first settlement in the area of the modern city dates to the 9th century B.C. Ambracia was founded as a [[Corinth]]ian [[colonies in antiquity|colony]] in the 7th century B.C. In 294 BC, after forty-three years of semi-autonomy under [[Macedon]]ian suzerainty, Ambracia was given to [[Pyrrhus of Epirus|Pyrrhus]], king of the [[Molossians]] and of [[Epirus (ancient state)|Epirus]], who made it his capital, using Ambracia as a base to attack the [[Roman Republic|Romans]]. Pyrrhus managed to achieve great but costly victories against the Romans, hence the phrase \"[[Pyrrhic victory]]\" which refers in particular to an exchange at the [[Battle of Asculum]]. Nevertheless, Pyrrhus found the time and means to adorn his capital with a palace, temples and theatres. In 146 BC, Ambracia became part of the [[Roman Republic]].\n\n===Middle Ages===\n{{further|Byzantine Greece}}\n\nDespite the existence several churches from the 9th and 10th centuries, Arta is first attested only in 1082, when the [[Normans]] under [[Bohemond I of Antioch|Bohemond]] laid siege to the city.{{sfn|Soustal|Koder|1981|page=113}} The origin and etymology of the name is uncertain and debated.{{sfn|Soustal|Koder|1981|page=114}} In the [[Komnenian period]], the city flourished as a commercial centre, with links to [[Venice]], and rose to become a [[bishopric]] by&nbsp;1157.{{sfn|Soustal|Koder|1981|page=113}}<ref name=\"ODB\">{{ODB | last = Gregory | first = Timothy E. | last2 = \u0160ev\u010denko | first2 = Nancy Patterson | title = Arta | pages = 191\u2013192 }}</ref> The Jewish traveller [[Benjamin of Tudela]] visited the area in 1165.{{sfn|Soustal|Koder|1981|page=113}}\n\n[[File:Church of St. Theodora (Arta) 3.jpg|thumb|left|Byzantine church of St [[Theodora of Arta]] (11th century)]]\n[[File:Byzantium1204.png|thumb|The [[Despotate of Epirus]] (green) in 1204]]\n\nBy the end of the 12th century, Arta probably formed a distinct fiscal district (''[[episkepsis]]'') within the wider [[theme (Byzantine district)|theme]] of [[Nicopolis (theme)|Nicopolis]].<ref name=\"ODB\"/> After the [[Siege of Constantinople (1204)|fall]] of [[Constantinople]] to the [[Fourth Crusade]], it is recorded as the ''pertinentia de Arta'' in the ''[[Partitio Romaniae]]'' treaty of 1204, and assigned to Venice.{{sfn|Soustal|Koder|1981|page=113}}\n\n[[File:\u0397 \u03a0\u03b1\u03c1\u03b7\u03b3\u03bf\u03c1\u03ae\u03c4\u03b9\u03c3\u03c3\u03b1.jpg|thumb|right|The 13th-century [[Church of the Parigoritissa]], formerly site of the [[Archaeological Collection of Arta]].]]\n[[File:Byzantine church of st Vasileios in Arta, Greece.jpg|thumb|Saint Basilios of the Agor\u00e1 (14-15th century)]]\n\nThe Venetians did not take control, however, for in 1205 [[Michael I Komnenos Doukas]] came to the city, succeeded its previous Byzantine governor, and quickly established a new principality, which is known by historians as the [[Despotate of Epirus]].{{sfn|Soustal|Koder|1981|page=113}} Arta remained the capital of the new principality for most of its history,{{sfn|Soustal|Koder|1981|page=113}} and flourished as a result. The city experienced considerable building activity, with the renovation of older churches and the construction of new ones, most notably the [[Church of the Parigoritissa]] and the [[Church of the Kato Panagia]].<ref name=\"ODB\"/> Sometime after 1227 it received fortifications,<ref name=\"ODB\"/> and was the site of regional Church councils in 1213, 1219, and 1225.{{sfn|Soustal|Koder|1981|page=113}} The 15th-century ''[[Chronicle of the Tocco]]'' describes it as \"the center of a fertile agricultural region with many water buffaloes, cows, and horses\". The city had trade links to Venice\u2014a Venetian consul is attested in 1284 and 1314/19{{sfn|Soustal|Koder|1981|page=113}}\u2014and Ragusa, exporting dried meat, lard, ham, furs, and [[indigo]]. Archaeological finds also attest to a local ceramic industry.<ref name=\"ODB\"/>\n\nAfter the [[Battle of Pelagonia]] in 1259, the city was occupied by the troops of the rival [[Byzantine Greeks|Greek]] successor state, the [[Empire of Nicaea]], (which restored the Byzantine Empire in 1261) but was soon recovered for Epirus by [[John I Doukas]].{{sfn|Soustal|Koder|1981|page=113}} Another attack by the Byzantine emperor [[Andronikos II Palaiologos]] in 1292, by land and sea, was unsuccessful.{{sfn|Soustal|Koder|1981|page=113}} In 1303, the city was besieged for a month by the [[Capetian House of Anjou|Angevins]] under [[Charles II of Naples]].{{sfn|Soustal|Koder|1981|page=113}} In 1313, much of the city was destroyed in a great fire.{{sfn|Soustal|Koder|1981|page=113}} In the next year, Byzantine troops under the ''[[pinkernes]]'' John attacked Epirus, including Arta.{{sfn|Soustal|Koder|1981|page=113}}\n\nIn 1318, the last male-line descendant of Michael I, [[Thomas I Komnenos Doukas]], was assassinated by his nephew, the [[Count of Cephalonia]] [[Nicholas Orsini]], and Epirus passed to the Italian [[Orsini]] family. Nicholas was in turn murdered in 1323 by his brother [[John II Orsini]]. In 1331 Arta, as well as [[Leucas]] and other areas, were occupied by [[Walter VI of Brienne]], and John Orsini was forced to accept Angevin suzerainty.{{sfn|Soustal|Koder|1981|page=113}} John's death in 1335 left Epirus in the weak hands of the young [[Nikephoros II Orsini]] and his mother [[Anna Palaiologina (daughter of Andronikos Angelos Palaiologos)|Anna Palaiologina]], and the Byzantine emperor [[Andronikos III Palaiologos]] availed himself of the opportunity to occupy and annex Epirus.{{sfn|Fine|1994|pp=253\u2013254}}\n\nByzantine rule was unpopular,{{sfn|Nicol|2010|pp=108ff}} and in 1339 a revolt broke out, with Arta joining it, under a certain Nicholas Basilitzes. Andronikos III and his commander-in-chief, [[John Kantakouzenos]], campaigned in person in Epirus and captured the rebel fortresses one by one, either by siege or through negotiations. By the end of 1340, Byzantine rule was restored, and [[John Angelos (sebastokrator)|John Angelos]] took his seat as imperial governor in Arta.{{sfn|Fine|1994|pp=254\u2013255}}{{sfn|Nicol|2010|pp=114\u2013121, 124}}\n\n[[File:The Greek defensive barrack of Arta, 1881.jpg|thumb|The Greek defensive barrack, 1881]]\n[[File:Clock Tower Arta Greece 5.jpg|thumb|Old photo of Arta with the clocktower, 1910]]\n\nAided by the [[Byzantine civil war of 1341\u20131347]] and an outbreak of the [[Black Death]] that devastated the region, Arta with the rest of Epirus fell under the rule of the [[Medieval Serbia|Serbian]] king [[Stefan Dushan]] in autumn 1347. Dushan's half-brother [[Simeon Uro\u0161]], who married John II Orsini's daughter [[Thomais Orsini]], was appointed governor of Epirus.{{sfn|Fine|1994|p=320}} The city remained part of the new [[Serbian Empire]] until Dushan's death in 1355. Nikephoros II Orsini recovered Epirus in 1356/7, but his death in the [[Battle of Achelous (1359)|Battle of Achelous]] against the [[Albanians|Albanian]] tribes that had invaded the region, meant that Arta returned to the (rather nominal) rule of Simeon Uro\u0161, who preferred to reside in [[Thessaly]] rather than Epirus.{{sfn|Soustal|Koder|1981|pp=70, 113\u2013114}}{{sfn|Fine|1994|pp=347\u2013350}}{{sfn|Nicol|2010|pp=123\u2013138}} This left Epirus open to increasing Albanian migration, who soon captured most of Epirus, except for [[Ioannina]].{{sfn|Fine|1994|pp=350\u2013351}} In 1367 or shortly after, Arta too was captured, and became the centre of the \"[[Despotate of Arta]]\", until 1374 under [[Peter Losha]] and then [[John Bua Spata]].{{sfn|Soustal|Koder|1981|page=114}} The Albanian rulers managed to withstand attacks by the Angevins (sometime between 1374 and 1384), as well as by the [[Grand Master of the Knights Hospitaller]] [[Juan Fern\u00e1ndez de Heredia]] in 1378, but in 1384 the city was plundered by the [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman Turks]].{{sfn|Soustal|Koder|1981|page=114}}\n\nFrom 1401/02, [[Carlo I Tocco]], the ambitious Count of Cephalonia, began launching attacks on Arta, taking advantage of the Albanians' infighting. Despite the Albanians' calling on Ottoman aid, in 1416 Tocco captured Arta after a long siege. Having taken control of Ioannina in 1411, Tocco thus reunited the core of the old Epirote realm, and received recognition from both the Ottomans and the Byzantine emperor.{{sfn|Soustal|Koder|1981|pp=72\u201373, 114}} After Carlo I's death in 1429, he was succeeded by his nephew [[Carlo II Tocco]]. In 1449, the city fell to the Ottomans.{{sfn|Soustal|Koder|1981|page=114}}\n\n===Ottoman period===\n{{further|Ottoman Greece}}\n\nUnder Ottoman rule, the town was called in Turkish ''Narda''. It was occupied by [[Republic of Venice|Venetians]] in 1717 and the French in 1797, but the Ottomans retook it in 1799. Several battles took place near the city during the [[Greek War of Independence]].\n\n===Modern era===\nThe city was finally annexed to the [[Greek Kingdom]] in 1881 with the [[Convention of Constantinople (1881)|Convention of Constantinople]].\n\n==Climate==\n\n{{Weather box\n|width=auto\n|location=Arta (1976-1997)\n|metric first=yes\n|single line=yes\n|Jan high C=13.3\n|Feb high C=14.0\n|Mar high C=16.7\n|Apr high C=20.1\n|May high C=25.0\n|Jun high C=29.1\n|Jul high C=31.8\n|Aug high C=32.0\n|Sep high C=29.0\n|Oct high C=24.1\n|Nov high C=19.0\n|Dec high C=14.9\n|year high C=\n|Jan mean C=8.7\n|Feb mean C=9.4\n|Mar mean C=11.9\n|Apr mean C=15.2\n|May mean C=19.9\n|Jun mean C=24.0\n|Jul mean C=26.5\n|Aug mean C=26.5\n|Sep mean C=23.1\n|Oct mean C=18.3\n|Nov mean C=13.5\n|Dec mean C=9.9\n|year mean C=\n|Jan low C=4.7\n|Feb low C=5.2\n|Mar low C=7.0\n|Apr low C=9.9\n|May low C=13.9\n|Jun low C=17.3\n|Jul low C=19.5\n|Aug low C=19.9\n|Sep low C=17.1\n|Oct low C=13.4\n|Nov low C=9.4\n|Dec low C=6.0\n|year low C=\n|rain colour = green\n|Jan rain mm=131.8\n|Feb rain mm=135.0\n|Mar rain mm=93.8\n|Apr rain mm=81.5\n|May rain mm=58.5\n|Jun rain mm=21.8\n|Jul rain mm=12.6\n|Aug rain mm=17.2\n|Sep rain mm=43.5\n|Oct rain mm=115.4\n|Nov rain mm=186.0\n|Dec rain mm=187.5\n|year rain mm=\n|Jan rain days=12.1\n|Feb rain days=11.1\n|Mar rain days=10.6\n|Apr rain days=9.6\n|May rain days=7.4\n|Jun rain days=4.2\n|Jul rain days=2.5\n|Aug rain days=2.5\n|Sep rain days=4.9\n|Oct rain days=8.1\n|Nov rain days=11.9\n|Dec rain days=13.0\n|year rain days=\n|Jan humidity=71.7\n|Feb humidity=70.6\n|Mar humidity=68.9\n|Apr humidity=68.8\n|May humidity=66.0\n|Jun humidity=61.4\n|Jul humidity=59.2\n|Aug humidity=59.4\n|Sep humidity=63.6\n|Oct humidity=67.7\n|Nov humidity=74.1\n|Dec humidity=73.2\n|year humidity=\n|source 1 = Hellenic National Meteorological Service <ref>{{cite web\n  | url=http://www.hnms.gr/hnms/greek/climatology/climatology_region_diagrams_html?dr_city=Arta\n  | title=Mean Arta Climatic Averages\n  | publisher=Hellenic National Meteorological Service\n  | accessdate=30 April 2015\n  | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160916091714/http://www.hnms.gr/hnms/greek/climatology/climatology_region_diagrams_html?dr_city=Arta\n  | archive-date=16 September 2016\n  | url-status=dead\n  }}</ref>\n  | date=April 2015\n}}\n\n==Landmarks==\n[[File:\u039d\u03b1\u03cc\u03c2 \u0391\u03c0\u03cc\u03bb\u03bb\u03c9\u03bd\u03b1 \u03a0\u03c5\u03b8\u03af\u03bf\u03c5 \u03a3\u03c9\u03c4\u03ae\u03c1\u03b1, \u0386\u03c1\u03c4\u03b1 1.JPG|thumb|Ruins of the ancient temple of Apollo P\u00fdthios Sot\u00edr]]\n[[File:Small theatre of Ambracia 1.jpg|thumb|Small ancient theatre]]\n\n===Classical===\nThe modern city is on the site of ancient [[Ambracia]]. Remains of the classic era include the ancient walls, the ruins of an ancient temple of [[Apollo]], a small theatre, and remnants of the southwest cemetery.\n\n===Byzantine and later===\n[[File:Arta Castle Greece 16.jpg|thumb|200px|View of the Byzantine castle]]\n[[File:Arta-clock tower.JPG|thumb|200px|Clocktower in front of the castle]]\n[[File:Kilkis square, Arta, Greece.jpg|thumb|200px|Kilkis Square]]\n[[File:Saint Demetrius church in Arta, Greece.jpg|thumb|200px|Saint Demetrius of Thessaloniki church]]\n[[File:Lake Arta Greece 5.JPG|thumb|200px|Artificial lake of Arta]]\n\nThe town's fortifications were built by [[Michael I Komnenos Doukas]] in the early 13th century, but their present form is largely post-Byzantine. Secular architecture from the Byzantine period, including the palace of the Despots of Epirus, has vanished completely, but the city preserves numerous churches.<ref name=\"ODB\"/>\n\nThe most important Byzantine church is the [[cathedral]] [[Church of the Paregoretissa]], built ca. 1290 by [[Nikephoros I Komnenos Doukas]] and his wife [[Anna Palaiologina Kantakouzene]]. Other important churches of the late Byzantine period are the [[Church of the Kato Panagia]], built by Nikephoros I's father [[Michael II Komnenos Doukas]], and the Monastery of Saint Theodora, housing the tomb of the city's patron, [[Theodora of Arta]].<ref name=\"ODB\"/> Several other churches dating to the 9th and 10th centuries also survive in and around the city: [[Saint Basil of the Bridge]], [[Saint Demetrios of Katsoures]] in [[Plisioi]], the [[Panagia Blacherna monastery]], the [[Panagia Vryoni]] in [[Neochoraki, Arta|Neochoraki]], the Red Church in [[Vourgareli]], the Panagia of Koronisia in [[Koronisia]] and the Church of the Pantanassa in [[Filippiada]].\n\n===Museums===\n*[[Archaeological Museum of Arta]]\n*[[Church of the Paregoretissa]]\n*Folk museum 'Skoufas'\n*Historical museum 'Skoufas'\n*Private folk museum in Kypseli.\n*Archaeological museum of Koronisia\n\n==Technological Educational Institute of Epirus==\n[[File:\u03a4\u03bc\u03ae\u03bc\u03b1 \u0391\u03bd\u03b8\u03bf\u03ba\u03bf\u03bc\u03af\u03b1\u03c2 \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u0391\u03c1\u03c7\u03b9\u03c4\u03b5\u03ba\u03c4\u03bf\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae\u03c2 \u03a4\u03bf\u03c0\u03af\u03bf\u03c5-\u03a4\u0395\u0399 \u0397\u03c0\u03b5\u03af\u03c1\u03bf\u03c5-\u0386\u03c1\u03c4\u03b1.JPG|thumb|A building of the [[Technological Educational Institute of Epirus]]]]\n\nThe Technological Educational Institute of Epirus (T.E.I.) [http://www.teiep.gr] has a main campus and its administration seat in Arta and has branch campuses in the three other main cities of Epirus, [[Ioannina]], [[Igoumenitsa]] and [[Preveza]]. It has four (4) Faculties and thirteen (13) Departments.\n\n==Transportation==\nArta is located NNW of [[Antirrio]], [[Messolongi]] and [[Agrinio]], NE of [[Preveza]], SSE of [[Ioannina]] and nearly SW of [[Trikala]].\n\nRegular bus lines connect Arta with all bigger Greek cities.\n(bus to Athens departs several times a day and trip takes about 5 hours)\n\nThe city is linked with the [[Greek National Road 5|GR-5]] (Antirrio - Ioannina) and the [[Greek National Road 30|GR-30]] which links with [[Peta, Greece|Peta]] and [[Trikala]].\nThe [[Arachthos River]] flows to the west with its reservoir lying directly to the north.\n\n==Municipality==\n[[File:2011 Dimos Artas.png|thumb|Arta municipality]]\n[[File:Nikolaos Skoufas pedestrian street in Arta, Greece.jpg|thumb|Skoufa Street]]\n[[File:Street market in Arta, Greece.jpg|thumb|Central street market]]\n\nThe present municipality Arta was formed at the 2011 local government reform by the merger of the following 5 former municipalities, that became municipal units (constituent communities in brackets):<ref name=Kallikratis>[http://www.kedke.gr/uploads2010/FEKB129211082010_kallikratis.pdf Kallikratis law] Greece Ministry of Interior {{in lang|el}}</ref>\n*[[Amvrakikos]] (Aneza, Vigla, Gavria, Kalogeriko, Koronisia, Polydroso, Rachi, Strongyli, Psathotopi)\n*'''Arta''' (Arta, Keramates, Kostakioi, [[Limini]])\n*[[Filothei, Arta|Filothei]] (Agios Spyridon, Kalamia, Kalovatos, Kirkizates, Rokka, Chalkiades)\n*[[Vlacherna]] (Vlacherna, Grammenitsa, Grimpovo, Korfovouni)\n*[[Xirovouni]] (Ammotopos, Dafnoti, Kampi, Pantanassa, Pistiana, Rodavgi, Skoupa, Faneromeni)\n\nThe municipality has an area of 457.248&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>, the municipal unit 47.493&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>.<ref name=stat01>{{cite web|url=http://dlib.statistics.gr/Book/GRESYE_02_0101_00098%20.pdf |publisher=National Statistical Service of Greece |title=Population & housing census 2001 (incl. area and average elevation) |language=el |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150921212047/http://dlib.statistics.gr/Book/GRESYE_02_0101_00098%20.pdf |archivedate=2015-09-21 }}</ref>\n\n===Quarters of Arta===\n*Agia Triada\n*Agioi Anargyroi\n*Agios Georgios Glykorrizou\n*Eleousa\n*Glykorrizo\n*Kato Panagia Artas\n*Marathovouni\n\n==Historical population==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- \n! Year !! Municipal unit !! Municipality\n|-\n| 1981 || 20,004 || -  \n|-\n| 1991 || 23,710 || - \n|-\n| 2001 || 23,863 || - \n|-\n| 2011 || 27,330 || 43,166 \n|}\n\n==Notable people==\n\n=== Ancient ===\n\n*[[Pyrrhus of Epirus|Pyrrhus]] (318 BC-272 BC), general and king of Epirus\n*[[Epicrates of Ambracia]] (4th century BC), comic poet\n*[[Silanus of Ambracia]] (5th century BC), soothsayer in [[Xenophon]]'s [[Anabasis (Xenophon)|''Anabasis'']]\n*[[Epigonus of Ambracia]] (6th-5th BC), musician\n\n=== Byzantine ===\n\n*[[Michael I Komnenos Doukas]], founder and first ruler of the [[Despotate of Epirus|principality of Epirus]] from 1205 until his death in 1215.\n*[[Theodore Komnenos Doukas]], (died c. 1253), ruler of [[Despotate of Epirus|Epirus]] from 1215 to 1230 and of Thessalonica from 1224 to 1230.\n* [[Theodora Petraliphaina]], [[canonized]] as '''Saint Theodora of Arta'''; (ca. 1225 \u2013 after 1270),  [[:wikt:consort|consort]] of [[Despotate of Epirus|Epirus]] and [[Eastern Orthodox Church|Orthodox Christian]] saint.\n* [[Michael II Komnenos Doukas]], ruler of [[Despotate of Epirus|Epirus]] from 1230 until his death in 1266/68.\n*[[Nikephoros I Komnenos Doukas]], (c. 1240 &ndash; c. 1297) ruler of [[Despotate of Epirus|Epirus]] from 1267/8 to c. 1297.\n* [[Thomas I Komnenos Doukas]],(c. 1285&ndash;1318) ruler of [[Despotate of Epirus|Epirus]] from c. 1297 until his death in 1318.\n\n=== Modern ===\n[[File:Skoufas.jpg|thumb|140px|[[Nikolaos Skoufas]]]]\n*[[Maximus the Greek]] (1475\u20131556),  monk, publicist, writer, scholar, humanist and translator\n*[[Nikolaos Skoufas]] (1779\u20131818), founder of the [[Filiki Eteria]], from [[Kompoti]]\n*[[Georgios Karaiskakis]] (1780\u20131827),hero of the [[Greek War of Independence]]\n*[[Theodoros Tzinis]] (1798\u20131869), fighter of the [[Greek War of Independence]], from [[Kompoti]]\n*[[Azmi \u00d6mer Akal\u0131n]], [[W\u0101li]] of [[Bursa]].<ref name=\"\u00d6zdalga2005\">{{cite book|last=\u00d6zdalga|first=Elisabeth|title=Late Ottoman society: the intellectual legacy|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sRtTyyGIgXsC&pg=PA332|accessdate=19 November 2010|year=2005|publisher=Psychology Press|isbn=978-0-415-34164-6|page=332}}</ref>\n*[[Hoca Ishak Efendi]] (1774\u20131835), Ottoman engineer and translator\n*[[Napoleon Zervas]] (1891\u20131957), WWII general and resistance leader\n*[[Konstantinos Karapanos]] (1840\u20131911),political and archaeologist\n*[[Alexandros Karapanos]] (1873\u20131946), politician and diplomat\n*[[Yiannis Moralis]] (1916-2009), painter\n*[[Olga Gerovasili]], politician\n*[[Antonios Nikopolidis]] (1971), footballer\n\n==Professional sports==\n'''Handball'''\n*https://web.archive.org/web/20070514042114/http://www.anagenisi-artas.gr/\n\n'''Basketball'''\n*[[Pyrros Artas]]\n\n'''Football'''\n*https://web.archive.org/web/20190207113340/http://www.anagenisiartas.gr/\n*https://web.archive.org/web/20061205033543/http://doxa-artas.gr/\n\n'''Volleyball'''\n*https://web.archive.org/web/20070516144231/http://www.anagenisi-artas.gr/volley/\n*http://www.filia.gr/\n\n==See also==\n*[[Despotate of Arta]]\n*[[Bridge of Arta]]\n*[[Arachthos River]]\n*[[Despotate of Epirus]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n{{refbegin|2}}\n* {{Cite book|ref=harv|last=Fine|first=John Van Antwerp Jr.|authorlink=John Van Antwerp Fine Jr.|title=The Late Medieval Balkans: A Critical Survey from the Late Twelfth Century to the Ottoman Conquest|year=1994|origyear=1987|location=Ann Arbor, Michigan|publisher=University of Michigan Press|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LvVbRrH1QBgC}}\n* {{cite book|last=Nicol|first=Donald MacGillivray|authorlink=Donald Nicol|title=The Despotate of Epiros 1267\u20131479: A Contribution to the History of Greece in the Middle Ages|location=Cambridge|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=2010|isbn=978-0-521-13089-9|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XIj0FfKto9AC|ref=harv}}\n* {{Tabula Imperii Byzantini | volume = 3}}\n* {{Cite book|ref=harv|last=Ze\u010devi\u0107|first=Nada|title=The Tocco of the Greek Realm: Nobility, Power and Migration in Latin Greece (14th-15th centuries)|year=2014|location=Belgrade|publisher=Makart|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LcqfAQAACAAJ}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.nomarxia-artas.gr Arta Prefecture]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060115070859/http://www.gtp.gr/LocPage.asp?id=2082 Municipality of Arta on GTP Travel Pages] (in English and Greek)\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060213105525/http://www.gtp.gr/LocPage.asp?id=2083 Arta (community) on GTP Travel Pages] (in English and Greek)\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110101160239/http://www.artasmuseum.gr/ Archaeological Museum of Arta] {{in lang|el}}\n\n{{Kallikratis-Epirus}}\n{{Arta div}}\n\n[[Category:Arta, Greece| ]]\n[[Category:Greek prefectural capitals]]\n[[Category:Municipalities of Epirus (region)]]\n[[Category:Burial sites of the Komnenodoukas dynasty]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Arta (regional unit)]]\n", "name_user": "2001:8004:c84:e8d0:e87b:ecd0:9c6a:9c34", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arta,_Greece"}
{"title_page": "KTM 300", "text_new": "{{Infobox motorcycle\n|name = KTM 300 EXC\n|image =[[File:Ktm xc 300.jpg|frameless|upright=1.35|KTM 300 XC]]\n|aka              =KTM 300 XC, KTM 300 XC-W\n|manufacturer = [[KTM|KTM-Sportmotorcycle AG]]\n|production       =\n|model_year = 1984-present\n|predecessor = KTM 300 GS\n|successor =\n|class = [[Enduro motorcycle|Enduro]]\n|engine  = [[Single-cylinder engine|Single-cylinder]], [[Radiator (engine cooling)#Automobiles and motorcycles|liquid-cooled]], [[Reed valve|Reed intake]], [[Fuel injection|Fuel injected]], [[2-stroke]]\n|bore_stroke      = 72&nbsp;mm / 72&nbsp;mm, 293&nbsp;cc\n|compression = 13.2:1<!--the compression has changed over time. as of 2018 it was up from 11.0 to 13.2-->\n|top_speed        =120 mi/h<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.topspeed.com/motorcycles/motorcycle-reviews/ktm/2008-ktm-300-xc-and-xc-w-e-ar51586.html|website=TopSpeed|title=2008 KTM 300 XC And XC-W (E)|accessdate=3 February 2016}}</ref> \n|power            =  {{convert|51|hp|abbr=on}}\n|torque           =\n|transmission =  5 or 6-speed, wet clutch, chain drive\n|suspension = Front: WP USD 48mm; fully adjustable<br>\nRear: WP single shock; fully adjustable\n|brakes = Hydraulic single disc\nFront :260mm (10.24\")\nRear: 220mm (8.66\")\n|tires = 90/90-21\"; 140/80-18\"\n|rake_trail       =26.5\u00b0, {{convert|4.4|in||abbr=on}}\n|ignition = Kokusan contactless, electronic, digital ignition timing adjustment\n|frame = Central double-cradle-type 25CrMo4 steel\n|wheelbase        = {{Convert|58.35|in|abbr=on}}\n|length           = <!--{{convert||mm|in||abbr=on}}-->\n|width            = <!--{{convert||mm|in||abbr=on}}-->\n|height           = <!--{{convert||mm|in||abbr=on}}-->\n|seat_height = {{Convert|37.8 to 38.8|in|abbr=on}}\n|fuel_capacity =  {{Convert|2.64-3.04|usgal|abbr=on}}\n|oil_capacity     =0.7 liters / 0.74 qt.\n|fuel_consumption =\n|turning_radius   =\n|dry_weight = {{Convert|221.0 to 225.1|lb|abbr=on}}\n|wet_weight =\n|related  = [[KTM 200|KTM 200 EXC]], KTM 250 EXC, [[Husaberg]]/[[Husqvarna Motorcycles|Husqvarna]] TE 300\n}}\n\nThe '''KTM 300''' is a series of [[two-stroke engine|2-stroke]] [[enduro]] [[Types of motorcycles#Off-road|off-road]] motorcycles made by [[KTM]]. They are the [[Penton]]-inspired 1984 '''300 GS''', the '''300 DMX''', the dirt only '''300 MXC''', European road legal '''300 EXC''' and their current US counterpart the '''300 XC''' (close-ratio) and '''300 XC-W''' ([[Gear train#Wide-ratio vs. close-ratio transmission|wide-ratio gear box]]) respectively. The KTM 300 is designed for difficult off-road conditions. The 300 EXC and the 300 XC-W have a small headlight, speedometer, tail-light and somewhat softer linkless PDS<ref name=\"PDS\" group=\"note\"/> suspension. Starting in 2008 all 300's came with electric start. Since the early 2000s KTM has been offering the XC-W model in a special \"Six-Days\" limited edition.\n\n==Model progression==\n<!--  THE FOLLOWING TABLE CONTAINS dummy DATA to demonstrate the syntax  -->\n\n===1984\u20131989===\nThe original 300GS Enduro grew out of the experience with 250&nbsp;cc Penton Hare Scrambler and other KTM [[Internal combustion engine cooling#Air-cooling|air cooled]] 2-stroke enduro bikes. Since the 1986 rules for the [[International Six Days Enduro]] (ISDE) for the open class allowed any bike larger that 250&nbsp;cc, KTM experimented with a water cooled over-250&nbsp;cc bike for the open class. They essentially bored their 250 out to 273&nbsp;cc and called it a 300. This version of the 300 was discontinued in 1987. KTM also tried [[Cylinder (engine)#Cylinder sleeving|sleeving down]] their 500mxc two-stroke to 350&nbsp;cc calling it the 350mxc, but the left side kick-starter and the right side chain were not popular.<ref name=\"all-about\">{{cite web|url=http://dirtbikemagazine.com/home-features/all-about-the-ktm-300-2-stroke|website=Dirt Bike Magazine|title=ALL ABOUT THE KTM 300 2-STROKE|accessdate=9 February 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Rousseau\">{{cite web|url=http://www.off-road.com/dirtbike/feature/2015-ktm-dualsport-and-crosscountry-dirt-bikes-53992.html|title=2015 KTM Dual-Sport and Cross-Country Dirt Bikes|author = Scott Rousseau|date=19 June 2015|website=Off-Road.com|accessdate=20 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n===1990\u20131997===\nIn 1990 KTM got serious and the present-day 300 was born.<ref name=\"all-about\"/>  Dubbed the 300 EX/C, its engine delivered very smooth power and did not produce a power hit. The bike performed well at low RPMs. In the mid-range and the top-end the smooth power delivery allowed the rider control over a wide variety of riding conditions from tight trails to wide open stretches. The plush suspension worked well compared to the older GS models.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.off-road.com/dirtbike/1990-ktm-300-22447.html|website=Off-Road.com|title=1990 KTM 300|accessdate=20 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe bike was also offered as the 300 DMX, a California desert version. These early KTM motors had 297&nbsp;cc displacement with 72&nbsp;mm x 73&nbsp;mm bore/stroke. Still the 300 hadn't reached its full potential. Ignition and jetting problems plagued these early models. In 1992 the company suffered financial woes and development was slowed.<ref name=\"all-about\"/> The 1993 KTMs had '''[[\u00d6hlins]]''' USD<ref name=\"USD\" group=\"note\"/> forks. WP forks were also used that year. In 1993 '''Motoplat''' went out of business, forcing KTM to switch to '''SEM''' ignition systems.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pentonracingproducts.com/motoplat-ignitions.shtml|website=Penton|title=motoplat systems and parts|accessdate=11 February 2016}}</ref> The 1996 model had '''[[Marzocchi]]''' USD forks and an \u00d6hlins rear shock absorber, a chrome exhaust pipe and silencer, a motor with better performance, increased cooling and stock '''Boyesen''' reeds. For 1996\u201397 the bike was offered in a 360&nbsp;cc version. In 1997 KTM switched to Kokusan ignition systems.<ref name=\"all-about\"/>\n\n===1998\u20132003===\n1998 was the first year for the KTM trademark orange bikes. In addition to larger capacity radiators, the 300 received KTM\u2019s PDS link-less  rear suspension with 320&nbsp;mm of rear wheel travel. The bike was again offered in a bored out 380&nbsp;cc during 1998-2000 (a street legal title was offered in some states). In 1999 the 300 received a hydraulic clutch and the 2000 motor benefited from a redesigned cylinder.\n\n===2004\u20132007===\nIn 2004 there was another frame change. There were significant engine changes, including a bore and stroke change and the carburetor size reduced from 38&nbsp;mm to 36&nbsp;mm, resulting in an {{Convert|8|lb|abbr=on}} weight savings and no more jetting problems.<ref name=\"all-about\"/>  For 2006, the US version of the 300 EXC was replaced by the XC and the XC-W. Both versions had 5-speed gearboxes and a stator for producing electricity. The 300 XC had a close-ratio gear box, no wiring for lights, and a stiffer suspension. The 300 XC-W had a wide-ratio gear box, head light, tail light and maintained the softer PDS suspension. The 2007 model had added a dual ignition mapping switch on the handlebar.\n\n===2008\u20132016===\nThe 2008 KTM 300 EXC is the first electric start two-stroke enduro bike to be released by a major manufacturer.  All models have PDS rear suspension.\n\nFor 2010, [[Husaberg]] the other KTM owned bike company, offered the '''TE300''', an XC-W with minor modifications to the bodywork and suspension settings.\n\nIn 2011, models received 6-speed gearboxes, a new exhaust pipe and silencer, and translucent fuel tanks.  The XC was also upgraded to a new frame, while retaining PDS rear suspension.  These frame updates did not make it to the XC-W until 2012.\n\nIn 2012 there were improvements to the starter motor bendix, more frame changes resulting in more wheel travel for models with PDS rear suspension (except the XC)<ref>Dirt Bike \"KTM Suspension Shootout: PDS vs. Lindage</ref>, and a new air box with a filter that can be replaced without the use of tools. The 300XC was changed from PDS rear suspension to linkage rear suspension.<ref>Dirt Bike \"KTM Suspension Shootout: PDS vs. Lindage</ref>  The 300XC-W models received the frame and bodywork updates that arrived in the XC line the year before, but also retain PDS rear suspension.\n\nIn 2013 the clutch was changed to a 'DDS' diaphragm spring clutch with lighter pull, a new stronger starter motor (350W motor was replaced with a 410W motor), lighter battery, and triple clamps changed from 22&nbsp;mm to 20&nbsp;mm offset.  The Husaberg TE300 was rebranded the [[Husqvarna Motorcycles|Husqvarna]] TE300 and also received linkage rear suspension.\n\nIn 2014 bikes received a new CDI unit and ignition curve, stronger/larger battery, changed jetting, updated brakes (front master cylinder, caliper, and pads changed), a redesigned cylinder head, new Boyesen reeds, stiffer seat foam, and a new rear shock absorber with revised settings.\n\nThe 2015 model chromoly steel frame is painted orange like the motocross models. All the 2015 models have the new '''WP''' 4CS forks with revised damping (rebound in one fork and compression in the other) with the ability to make adjustments on the fly, and a smaller front axle. The triple clamps have 2&nbsp;mm less offset resulting in more trail and different steering characteristics. The rear shock is longer but the travel is unchanged. The electric starter has different gearing to provide higher initial torque from the electric motor, and the battery is lighter and stronger.<ref name=\"ultimate\">{{cite web|url=http://dirtbikemagazine.com/home-features/is-this-the-ultimate-2-stroke-ktm-300xc-test|website=Dirt Bike Magazine|title=KTM 300XC: ULTIMATE 2-STROKE OR ULTIMATE DIRT BIKE?|accessdate=11 February 2016}}</ref> <ref name=\"first looks\">{{cite web|url=http://www.motorcycle-usa.com/2015/05/article/2016-ktm-xc-w-models-first-looks/|website=Moto USA|title=2016 KTM 300 XC-W Models First Looks|accessdate=12 February 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Rousseau\"/>\n\n===2017\u2013 Present===\n[[File:2017 KTM 300 XC-W Six Days.jpg|thumb|left|KTM 300 XC-W Six-Days Spain Edition]]The 2017 KTM 300's are completely redesigned bikes. A counter-balancer has been added to reduce motor vibration. The case is a new design featuring a new position for the starter motor. A [[Mikuni (company)|Mikuni]] carb replaced the [[Keihin Corporation|Keihin]] carburetor as Keihin focuses on fuel injection. Suspension changed with the addition of a new Xplor 48 rear shock downsized from 50&nbsp;mm to 46&nbsp;mm. The forks are similar to the previous generation open cartridge forks supplied on the 300's with split compression and rebound adjusters. The adjuster atop the left fork controls compression and adjuster top the right fork controls rebound similar to the 4CS fork system.\n\nFor 2018 KTM started offering the 300 EXC (Europe only) model with transfer port injection (TPI) and with oil injection through the 39&nbsp;mm Dell\u2019Orto throttle body to meet [[European emission standards|EURO 4 standards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dirtbiketest.com/fresh-dirt/2018-ktm-250300-excxc-w-tpi-riding-impression/#FoZegoB3fpwgvYQg.99|website=Dirtbike Test|title=2018 KTM 250/300 EXC/XC-W TPI Riding Impression|author=Jimmy Lewis|accessdate=19 December 2017}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dirtbikemagazine.com/2018-ktm-two-strokes-both-efi-carbs/|website=Dirt Bike|title=2018 KTM TWO-STROKES: BOTH EFI & CARBS|accessdate=19 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nFor 2019 KTM began offering U.S. customers the 300 XC-W model with (TPI) and oil injection.  The fuel injected 300's were previously available only in the international market. The KTM XC-W still comes with PDS rear suspension while the 300 XC and the Husqvarna TE (essentially a KTM with different plastics) come with linkage suspensions.\n\nFor the 2020 model year KTM began providing U.S. customers both the 300 XC-W and 300 XC with TPI and oil injection, thus eliminating all carbureted 300's from the US market. Both models benefit from updated EFI maping and a new air pressure sensor. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dirtrider.com/2020-ktm-300-xc-tpi-first-ride-review/|website=Dirtbike Rider|title=2020 KTM 300 XC TPI First Ride Review|author=Andrew Oldar|date=5 August 2019|accessdate=25 November 2019}}</ref> The XC-W has been given an all new chassis derived from the SX models.\n\n==Notes {{Anchor|References|Notes|Footnotes}} ==\n<references group=\"note\">\n<ref name=\"PDS\" group=\"note\">PDS is an [[wikt: initialism|initialism]] for <u>P</u>rogressive <u>D</u>amping <u>S</u>ystem when referring to rear shock absorbers in non-linkage rear suspensions.\"</ref>\n<ref name=\"USD\" group=\"note\">USD is an initialism for <u>U</u>p<u>S</u>ide <u>D</u>own when referring to telescopic forks on modern motorcycles.\"</ref>\n</references>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://www.ktm.com}}\n\n[[Category:KTM motorcycles]]\n[[Category:Off-road motorcycles]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox motorcycle\n|name = KTM 300 EXC\n|image =[[File:Ktm xc 300.jpg|frameless|upright=1.35|KTM 300 XC]]\n|aka              =KTM 300 XC, KTM 300 XC-W\n|manufacturer = [[KTM|KTM-Sportmotorcycle AG]]\n|production       =\n|model_year = 1984-present\n|predecessor = KTM 300 GS\n|successor =\n|class = [[Enduro motorcycle|Enduro]]\n|engine  = [[Single-cylinder engine|Single-cylinder]], [[Radiator (engine cooling)#Automobiles and motorcycles|liquid-cooled]], [[Reed valve|Reed intake]], [[Fuel injection|Fuel injected]], [[2-stroke]]\n|bore_stroke      = 72&nbsp;mm / 72&nbsp;mm, 293&nbsp;cc\n|compression = 13.2:1<!--the compression has changed over time. as of 2018 it was up from 11.0 to 13.2-->\n|top_speed        =120 mi/h<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.topspeed.com/motorcycles/motorcycle-reviews/ktm/2008-ktm-300-xc-and-xc-w-e-ar51586.html|website=TopSpeed|title=2008 KTM 300 XC And XC-W (E)|accessdate=3 February 2016}}</ref> \n|power            =  {{convert|51|hp|abbr=on}}\n|torque           =\n|transmission =  5 or 6-speed, wet clutch, chain drive\n|suspension = Front: WP USD 48mm; fully adjustable<br>\nRear: WP single shock; fully adjustable\n|brakes = Hydraulic single disc\nFront :260mm (10.24\")\nRear: 220mm (8.66\")\n|tires = 90/90-21\"; 140/80-18\"\n|rake_trail       =26.5\u00b0, {{convert|4.4|in||abbr=on}}\n|ignition = Kokusan contactless, electronic, digital ignition timing adjustment\n|frame = Central double-cradle-type 25CrMo4 steel\n|wheelbase        = {{Convert|58.35|in|abbr=on}}\n|length           = <!--{{convert||mm|in||abbr=on}}-->\n|width            = <!--{{convert||mm|in||abbr=on}}-->\n|height           = <!--{{convert||mm|in||abbr=on}}-->\n|seat_height = {{Convert|37.8 to 38.8|in|abbr=on}}\n|fuel_capacity =  {{Convert|2.64-3.04|usgal|abbr=on}}\n|oil_capacity     =0.7 liters / 0.74 qt.\n|fuel_consumption =\n|turning_radius   =\n|dry_weight = {{Convert|221.0 to 225.1|lb|abbr=on}}\n|wet_weight =\n|related  = [[KTM 200|KTM 200 EXC]], KTM 250 EXC, [[Husaberg]]/[[Husqvarna Motorcycles|Husqvarna]] TE 300\n}}\n\nThe '''KTM 300''' is a series of [[two-stroke engine|2-stroke]] [[enduro]] [[Types of motorcycles#Off-road|off-road]] motorcycles made by [[KTM]]. They are the [[Penton]]-inspired 1984 '''300 GS''', the '''300 DMX''', the dirt only '''300 MXC''', European road legal '''300 EXC''' and their current US counterpart the '''300 XC''' (close-ratio) and '''300 XC-W''' ([[Gear train#Wide-ratio vs. close-ratio transmission|wide-ratio gear box]]) respectively. The KTM 300 is designed for difficult off-road conditions. The 300 EXC and the 300 XC-W have a small headlight, speedometer, tail-light and somewhat softer linkless PDS<ref name=\"PDS\" group=\"note\"/> suspension. Starting in 2008 all 300's came with electric start. Since the early 2000's KTM has been offering the XC-W model in a special \"Six-Days\" limited edition.\n\n==Model progression==\n<!--  THE FOLLOWING TABLE CONTAINS dummy DATA to demonstrate the syntax  -->\n\n===1984\u20131989===\nThe original 300GS Enduro grew out of the experience with 250&nbsp;cc Penton Hare Scrambler and other KTM [[Internal combustion engine cooling#Air-cooling|air cooled]] 2-stroke enduro bikes. Since the 1986 rules for the [[International Six Days Enduro]] (ISDE) for the open class allowed any bike larger that 250&nbsp;cc, KTM experimented with a water cooled over-250&nbsp;cc bike for the open class. They essentially bored their 250 out to 273&nbsp;cc and called it a 300. This version of the 300 was discontinued in 1987. KTM also tried [[Cylinder (engine)#Cylinder sleeving|sleeving down]] their 500mxc two-stroke to 350&nbsp;cc calling it the 350mxc, but the left side kick-starter and the right side chain were not popular.<ref name=\"all-about\">{{cite web|url=http://dirtbikemagazine.com/home-features/all-about-the-ktm-300-2-stroke|website=Dirt Bike Magazine|title=ALL ABOUT THE KTM 300 2-STROKE|accessdate=9 February 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Rousseau\">{{cite web|url=http://www.off-road.com/dirtbike/feature/2015-ktm-dualsport-and-crosscountry-dirt-bikes-53992.html|title=2015 KTM Dual-Sport and Cross-Country Dirt Bikes|author = Scott Rousseau|date=19 June 2015|website=Off-Road.com|accessdate=20 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n===1990\u20131997===\nIn 1990 KTM got serious and the present-day 300 was born.<ref name=\"all-about\"/>  Dubbed the 300 EX/C, its engine delivered very smooth power and did not produce a power hit. The bike performed well at low RPMs. In the mid-range and the top-end the smooth power delivery allowed the rider control over a wide variety of riding conditions from tight trails to wide open stretches. The plush suspension worked well compared to the older GS models.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.off-road.com/dirtbike/1990-ktm-300-22447.html|website=Off-Road.com|title=1990 KTM 300|accessdate=20 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe bike was also offered as the 300 DMX, a California desert version. These early KTM motors had 297&nbsp;cc displacement with 72&nbsp;mm x 73&nbsp;mm bore/stroke. Still the 300 hadn't reached its full potential. Ignition and jetting problems plagued these early models. In 1992 the company suffered financial woes and development was slowed.<ref name=\"all-about\"/> The 1993 KTMs had '''[[\u00d6hlins]]''' USD<ref name=\"USD\" group=\"note\"/> forks. WP forks were also used that year. In 1993 '''Motoplat''' went out of business, forcing KTM to switch to '''SEM''' ignition systems.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pentonracingproducts.com/motoplat-ignitions.shtml|website=Penton|title=motoplat systems and parts|accessdate=11 February 2016}}</ref> The 1996 model had '''[[Marzocchi]]''' USD forks and an \u00d6hlins rear shock absorber, a chrome exhaust pipe and silencer, a motor with better performance, increased cooling and stock '''Boyesen''' reeds. For 1996\u201397 the bike was offered in a 360&nbsp;cc version. In 1997 KTM switched to Kokusan ignition systems.<ref name=\"all-about\"/>\n\n===1998\u20132003===\n1998 was the first year for the KTM trademark orange bikes. In addition to larger capacity radiators, the 300 received KTM\u2019s PDS link-less  rear suspension with 320&nbsp;mm of rear wheel travel. The bike was again offered in a bored out 380&nbsp;cc during 1998-2000 (a street legal title was offered in some states). In 1999 the 300 received a hydraulic clutch and the 2000 motor benefited from a redesigned cylinder.\n\n===2004\u20132007===\nIn 2004 there was another frame change. There were significant engine changes, including a bore and stroke change and the carburetor size reduced from 38&nbsp;mm to 36&nbsp;mm, resulting in an {{Convert|8|lb|abbr=on}} weight savings and no more jetting problems.<ref name=\"all-about\"/>  For 2006, the US version of the 300 EXC was replaced by the XC and the XC-W. Both versions had 5-speed gearboxes and a stator for producing electricity. The 300 XC had a close-ratio gear box, no wiring for lights, and a stiffer suspension. The 300 XC-W had a wide-ratio gear box, head light, tail light and maintained the softer PDS suspension. The 2007 model had added a dual ignition mapping switch on the handlebar.\n\n===2008\u20132016===\nThe 2008 KTM 300 EXC is the first electric start two-stroke enduro bike to be released by a major manufacturer.  All models have PDS rear suspension.\n\nFor 2010, [[Husaberg]] the other KTM owned bike company, offered the '''TE300''', an XC-W with minor modifications to the bodywork and suspension settings.\n\nIn 2011, models received 6-speed gearboxes, a new exhaust pipe and silencer, and translucent fuel tanks.  The XC was also upgraded to a new frame, while retaining PDS rear suspension.  These frame updates did not make it to the XC-W until 2012.\n\nIn 2012 there were improvements to the starter motor bendix, more frame changes resulting in more wheel travel for models with PDS rear suspension (except the XC)<ref>Dirt Bike \"KTM Suspension Shootout: PDS vs. Lindage</ref>, and a new air box with a filter that can be replaced without the use of tools. The 300XC was changed from PDS rear suspension to linkage rear suspension.<ref>Dirt Bike \"KTM Suspension Shootout: PDS vs. Lindage</ref>  The 300XC-W models received the frame and bodywork updates that arrived in the XC line the year before, but also retain PDS rear suspension.\n\nIn 2013 the clutch was changed to a 'DDS' diaphragm spring clutch with lighter pull, a new stronger starter motor (350W motor was replaced with a 410W motor), lighter battery, and triple clamps changed from 22&nbsp;mm to 20&nbsp;mm offset.  The Husaberg TE300 was rebranded the [[Husqvarna Motorcycles|Husqvarna]] TE300 and also received linkage rear suspension.\n\nIn 2014 bikes received a new CDI unit and ignition curve, stronger/larger battery, changed jetting, updated brakes (front master cylinder, caliper, and pads changed), a redesigned cylinder head, new Boyesen reeds, stiffer seat foam, and a new rear shock absorber with revised settings.\n\nThe 2015 model chromoly steel frame is painted orange like the motocross models. All the 2015 models have the new '''WP''' 4CS forks with revised damping (rebound in one fork and compression in the other) with the ability to make adjustments on the fly, and a smaller front axle. The triple clamps have 2&nbsp;mm less offset resulting in more trail and different steering characteristics. The rear shock is longer but the travel is unchanged. The electric starter has different gearing to provide higher initial torque from the electric motor, and the battery is lighter and stronger.<ref name=\"ultimate\">{{cite web|url=http://dirtbikemagazine.com/home-features/is-this-the-ultimate-2-stroke-ktm-300xc-test|website=Dirt Bike Magazine|title=KTM 300XC: ULTIMATE 2-STROKE OR ULTIMATE DIRT BIKE?|accessdate=11 February 2016}}</ref> <ref name=\"first looks\">{{cite web|url=http://www.motorcycle-usa.com/2015/05/article/2016-ktm-xc-w-models-first-looks/|website=Moto USA|title=2016 KTM 300 XC-W Models First Looks|accessdate=12 February 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Rousseau\"/>\n\n===2017\u2013 Present===\n[[File:2017 KTM 300 XC-W Six Days.jpg|thumb|left|KTM 300 XC-W Six-Days Spain Edition]]The 2017 KTM 300's are completely redesigned bikes. A counter-balancer has been added to reduce motor vibration. The case is a new design featuring a new position for the starter motor. A [[Mikuni (company)|Mikuni]] carb replaced the [[Keihin Corporation|Keihin]] carburetor as Keihin focuses on fuel injection. Suspension changed with the addition of a new Xplor 48 rear shock downsized from 50&nbsp;mm to 46&nbsp;mm. The forks are similar to the previous generation open cartridge forks supplied on the 300's with split compression and rebound adjusters. The adjuster atop the left fork controls compression and adjuster top the right fork controls rebound similar to the 4CS fork system.\n\nFor 2018 KTM started offering the 300 EXC (Europe only) model with transfer port injection (TPI) and with oil injection through the 39&nbsp;mm Dell\u2019Orto throttle body to meet [[European emission standards|EURO 4 standards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dirtbiketest.com/fresh-dirt/2018-ktm-250300-excxc-w-tpi-riding-impression/#FoZegoB3fpwgvYQg.99|website=Dirtbike Test|title=2018 KTM 250/300 EXC/XC-W TPI Riding Impression|author=Jimmy Lewis|accessdate=19 December 2017}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dirtbikemagazine.com/2018-ktm-two-strokes-both-efi-carbs/|website=Dirt Bike|title=2018 KTM TWO-STROKES: BOTH EFI & CARBS|accessdate=19 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nFor 2019 KTM began offering U.S. customers the 300 XC-W model with (TPI) and oil injection.  The fuel injected 300's were previously available only in the international market. The KTM XC-W still comes with PDS rear suspension while the 300 XC and the Husqvarna TE (essentially a KTM with different plastics) come with linkage suspensions.\n\nFor the 2020 model year KTM began providing U.S. customers both the 300 XC-W and 300 XC with TPI and oil injection, thus eliminating all carbureted 300's from the US market. Both models benefit from updated EFI maping and a new air pressure sensor. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dirtrider.com/2020-ktm-300-xc-tpi-first-ride-review/|website=Dirtbike Rider|title=2020 KTM 300 XC TPI First Ride Review|author=Andrew Oldar|date=5 August 2019|accessdate=25 November 2019}}</ref> The XC-W has been given an all new chassis derived from the SX models.\n\n==Notes {{Anchor|References|Notes|Footnotes}} ==\n<references group=\"note\">\n<ref name=\"PDS\" group=\"note\">PDS is an [[wikt: initialism|initialism]] for <u>P</u>rogressive <u>D</u>amping <u>S</u>ystem when referring to rear shock absorbers in non-linkage rear suspensions.\"</ref>\n<ref name=\"USD\" group=\"note\">USD is an initialism for <u>U</u>p<u>S</u>ide <u>D</u>own when referring to telescopic forks on modern motorcycles.\"</ref>\n</references>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://www.ktm.com}}\n\n[[Category:KTM motorcycles]]\n[[Category:Off-road motorcycles]]\n", "name_user": "Alistair1978", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/KTM_300"}
